{
  "Firm Name" : "EQUITY SERVICES, INC.",
  "Termination Type" : "Discharged",
  "Allegations" : "UPON RECEIPT OF CORRESPONDENCE SENT TO OUR LIFE INSURANCE AFFILIATE, THE FIRM LEARNED THAT MR. LAMENDOLA WROTE A CUSTOMER A CHECK FOR AN INTEREST CREDITING METHOD ON A FIXED ANNUITY. NONE OF THIS CORRESPONDENCE, WHICH INCLUDED CORRESPONDENCE BETWEEN THE REPRESENTATIVE AND THE CUSTOMER, IS BELIEVED TO HAVE RUN THROUGH THE FIRM.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, THE FIRM LEARNED THAT THE INTEREST CREDITING METHOD AT ISSUE WAS NOT OFFERED BY THE LIFE INSURANCE AFFILIATE.  FURTHER, THE FIRM LEARNED THAT THE REPRESENTATIVE ALTERED AND PROVIDED A DOCUMENT TO THE CLIENT TO SUGGEST THAT THE INTEREST CREDITING METHOD WAS IN FACT OFFERED.",
  "Broker Comment" : "AFTER REPEATED, UNSUCCESSFUL ATTEMPTS TO HAVE THE INSURANCE COMPANY CORRECT MY CLIENT'S ANNUITY, I WROTE THE CLIENT A CHECK IN ORDER TO MAKE HIM WHOLE.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THE PRODUCT INVOLVED IS NOT A SECURITY. ALSO, MY COMMISSIONS WERE RECEIVED DIRECTLY FROM THE INSURANCE COMPANY AND DID NOT FLOW THROUGH THE BROKER/DEALER.  CERTAIN EMAIL COMMUNICATIONS WERE IN FACT SENT FROM A FIRM-APPROVED EMAIL ADDRESS AND CAPTURED FOR REVIEW BY THE FIRM.  HOWEVER, IT WAS MY UNDERSTANDING THAT COMMUNICATIONS INVOLVING INSURANCE PRODUCTS THAT DID NOT PASS THROUGH THE B/D WERE EXEMPT FROM THE EMAIL REVIEW REQUIREMENT.  AS SUCH, SOME COMMUNICATIONS WERE SENT FROM MY PERSONAL EMAIL ACCOUNT. THE ANNUITY INVESTED IN AN INTEREST CREDITING METHOD (\"ICM\") THAT WAS IN FACT OFFERED BY THE LIFE INSURANCE AFFILIATE. HOWEVER, IN ONE COMMUNICATION I PROVIDED THE CLIENT WITH A WRITTEN ABBREVIATED DESCRIPTION OF THE ICM.  I INADVERTENTLY USED A NAME OF AN ICM THAT WAS NOT OFFERED BY THE FIRM WHEN I INTENDED TO REFERENCE THE ICM OFFERED BY THE FIRM.  THE ANNUITY APPLICATION AND OTHER DOCUMENTS ALL PROPERLY REFERENCE THE ICM OFFERED BY THE FIRM.  THIS WAS NOT AN ATTEMPT TO DECEIVE THE CLIENT BUT RATHER AN HONEST MISTAKE."
}

